A placebo test is a type of experimental research study in which a fake or inert treatment is used as a control or comparison group. This treatment is designed to look and be like the treatment or intervention being tested, but without any actual known effects. The idea is that any real effects of the treatments being tested will show up in the placebo group, since many illnesses or conditions have symptoms that mimic those of the treatments. In simple algorithms for solving the Navier-Stokes equations, like the upwind algorithm or a compact finite-difference scheme, the PRCE scheme considers the value of the velocity at each point in time. This value is then used to calculate the current value of the pressure across the grid. In order for the solution to remain accurate, the approach requires that the partial derivatives of velocity are used to compute the values of the derivative of the pressure. Since the gradient of density cannot be directly used, velocity is the derivative that couples to the velocity field. Thus, when using pressure-coupled schemes, the velocity field is used to calculate the derivative of the pressure, leading to the definition of pressure as a function of velocity.
